    },
    {
      "id": "q-sc1S2DJvDp4SnFWBwFy",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -670.5616199285718,
      "y": 2292.3373652171,
      "width": 1670.1483154296875,
      "height": 1263.6000000000001,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#e9ecef",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b11",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 675046777,
      "version": 68,
      "versionNonce": 1638127031,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1781294376084,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Key Architecture Choices\n\n1. Use Next.js as the main app\nUse Next.js + TypeScript as the core project.\n\nWhy:\nIt supports normal pages, SEO-friendly routes, image optimization, and server-side logic in one project.\nYou avoid maintaining a separate frontend and backend at the beginning.\nIt is modern, widely used, and good for learning real full-stack patterns.\n\nPros:\nProfessional and scalable.\nGreat for SEO, which matters for artists.\nCan start simple and grow into backend/database/payment features later.\nTypeScript helps catch mistakes early.\n\nCons:\nMore concepts than plain HTML/CSS.\nYou need to learn routing, components, server/client boundaries, and deployment.\n\nNext.js app\n  frontend pages\n  server actions / API routes\n  structured painting data\n\nThis gives you a backend capability without creating a separate backend service.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Key Architecture Choices\n\n1. Use Next.js as the main app\nUse Next.js + TypeScript as the core project.\n\nWhy:\nIt supports normal pages, SEO-friendly routes, image optimization, and server-side logic in one project.\nYou avoid maintaining a separate frontend and backend at the beginning.\nIt is modern, widely used, and good for learning real full-stack patterns.\n\nPros:\nProfessional and scalable.\nGreat for SEO, which matters for artists.\nCan start simple and grow into backend/database/payment features later.\nTypeScript helps catch mistakes early.\n\nCons:\nMore concepts than plain HTML/CSS.\nYou need to learn routing, components, server/client boundaries, and deployment.\n\nNext.js app\n  frontend pages\n  server actions / API routes\n  structured painting data\n\nThis gives you a backend capability without creating a separate backend service.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "qvXzARKmglfM93fDNqqxE",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -670.5616202619054,
      "y": 3625.8040322171,
      "width": 1361.4842529296875,
      "height": 1846.8,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#6741d9",
      "backgroundColor": "#e9ecef",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b12",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2029523767,
      "version": 21,
      "versionNonce": 1680698231,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1781295160118,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "2. Do not use a database in v1\nStart with painting records in a local data file.\nExample concept:\n{\n  title: \"Evening Light\",\n  slug: \"evening-light\",\n  medium: \"Oil on canvas\",\n  dimensions: \"60 x 80 cm\",\n  priceNok: 12000,\n  status: \"available\",\n  images: [\"/paintings/evening-light/main.jpg\"]\n}\n\nWhy:\nYour mom does not need an admin dashboard yet.\nYou avoid database setup, authentication, migrations, permissions, and admin UI.\nFor a small number of paintings, code-managed content is clean and reliable.\n\nPros:\nSimple.\nFast to build.\nEasy to version with Git.\nGreat for learning data modeling before adding a real database.\n\nCons:\nYour mom cannot update paintings herself.\nEvery content update requires a code change and redeploy.\nNot ideal if there are many artworks or frequent updates.\n\nFuture upgrade:\nAdd a database or CMS when updating paintings becomes annoying.\n\nGood future options:\nSupabase/Postgres if you want to learn real backend/database development.\nSanity/Contentful/Strapi if the main goal is easy content editing.\nShopify/WooCommerce only if the project becomes a real shop with many products.\n\n",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "2. Do not use a database in v1\nStart with painting records in a local data file.\nExample concept:\n{\n  title: \"Evening Light\",\n  slug: \"evening-light\",\n  medium: \"Oil on canvas\",\n  dimensions: \"60 x 80 cm\",\n  priceNok: 12000,\n  status: \"available\",\n  images: [\"/paintings/evening-light/main.jpg\"]\n}\n\nWhy:\nYour mom does not need an admin dashboard yet.\nYou avoid database setup, authentication, migrations, permissions, and admin UI.\nFor a small number of paintings, code-managed content is clean and reliable.\n\nPros:\nSimple.\nFast to build.\nEasy to version with Git.\nGreat for learning data modeling before adding a real database.\n\nCons:\nYour mom cannot update paintings herself.\nEvery content update requires a code change and redeploy.\nNot ideal if there are many artworks or frequent updates.\n\nFuture upgrade:\nAdd a database or CMS when updating paintings becomes annoying.\n\nGood future options:\nSupabase/Postgres if you want to learn real backend/database development.\nSanity/Contentful/Strapi if the main goal is easy content editing.\nShopify/WooCommerce only if the project becomes a real shop with many products.\n\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "3oOQzX5vFe29yuZ5gSbZJ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -670.5616195952387,
      "y": 5432.470697883767,
      "width": 1711.4764404296875,
      "height": 1020.6,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#f08c00",
      "backgroundColor": "#e9ecef",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b13",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 767680697,
      "version": 23,
      "versionNonce": 1523523065,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1781295162679,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "3. Do not build a cart in v1\nDo not create shopping_cart records yet.\n\nWhy:\nPaintings are usually unique one-of-one items.\nA cart makes more sense when users commonly buy multiple products.\nIt adds complexity around reservations, stale carts, sold items, checkout expiration, and inventory locking.\n\nPros of skipping cart:\nMuch simpler.\nFewer edge cases.\nBetter fit for art sales.\n\nCons:\nBuyers cannot buy multiple paintings in one checkout.\nYou cannot support classic webshop behavior yet.\n\nRecommended v1 behavior:\nPainting detail page\n  -> \"Inquire about this painting\"\n  -> buyer sends name, email, message, painting id",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "3. Do not build a cart in v1\nDo not create shopping_cart records yet.\n\nWhy:\nPaintings are usually unique one-of-one items.\nA cart makes more sense when users commonly buy multiple products.\nIt adds complexity around reservations, stale carts, sold items, checkout expiration, and inventory locking.\n\nPros of skipping cart:\nMuch simpler.\nFewer edge cases.\nBetter fit for art sales.\n\nCons:\nBuyers cannot buy multiple paintings in one checkout.\nYou cannot support classic webshop behavior yet.\n\nRecommended v1 behavior:\nPainting detail page\n  -> \"Inquire about this painting\"\n  -> buyer sends name, email, message, painting id",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "pAo2EfBtWKTau2Iqrp-QV",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -670.5616195952388,
      "y": 6512.337364883767,
      "width": 1771.3804931640625,
      "height": 1263.6000000000001,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#c2255c",
      "backgroundColor": "#e9ecef",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b14",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 739816377,
      "version": 13,
      "versionNonce": 1381469177,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1781295410668,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "4. Use inquiry-first sales\nUse a form instead of immediate payment.\nWhy:\nYou chose Norway-first and developer-managed content.\nFor original art, you may need to confirm shipping, pickup, framing, and whether the painting is still available.\nIt avoids payment/refund problems if a painting was sold offline but the website was not updated yet.\nInquiry form fields:\nName\nEmail\nPhone, optional\nPainting title/id\nMessage\nConsent checkbox for being contacted\nServer behavior:\nValidate fields.\nSend email to artist/site owner.\nOptionally send buyer a confirmation email.\nShow success/failure state.\nPros:\nVery practical for v1.\nAvoids legal/payment complexity early.\nLets you learn forms, validation, server actions, and email.\nCons:\nBuyer cannot complete purchase instantly.\nManual follow-up required.\nSales process depends on response time.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "4. Use inquiry-first sales\nUse a form instead of immediate payment.\nWhy:\nYou chose Norway-first and developer-managed content.\nFor original art, you may need to confirm shipping, pickup, framing, and whether the painting is still available.\nIt avoids payment/refund problems if a painting was sold offline but the website was not updated yet.\nInquiry form fields:\nName\nEmail\nPhone, optional\nPainting title/id\nMessage\nConsent checkbox for being contacted\nServer behavior:\nValidate fields.\nSend email to artist/site owner.\nOptionally send buyer a confirmation email.\nShow success/failure state.\nPros:\nVery practical for v1.\nAvoids legal/payment complexity early.\nLets you learn forms, validation, server actions, and email.\nCons:\nBuyer cannot complete purchase instantly.\nManual follow-up required.\nSales process depends on response time.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "mY3_arHyPmhqw0UrP8BPA",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -667.2282869285721,
      "y": 7859.004031550434,
      "width": 2512.116943359375,
      "height": 1117.8,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#343a40",
      "backgroundColor": "#e9ecef",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b15",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1821454935,
      "version": 15,
      "versionNonce": 1832838519,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1781295577539,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "5. Add Vipps later, not now\nFor Norway-first direct payment, Vipps MobilePay ePayment is the natural future option.\n\nWhy:\nVipps is familiar to Norwegian buyers.\nVipps MobilePay’s current ePayment API supports online payments and multiple payment methods.\nTheir docs say ePayment replaces the older eCom API, so avoid building against legacy eCom.\n\nUse Vipps when:\nYou want “Buy now” for available paintings.\nPrices and shipping are predictable.\nYou are ready to handle payment webhooks and order state.\n\nDo not use Vipps yet because:\nDirect payment requires backend logic.\nYou need merchant setup, API keys, test/prod environments, payment status handling, and failure handling.\nYou need to prevent two people from buying the same painting.\nStripe Checkout is a good future alternative if international buyers matter. Stripe gives hosted checkout, card payments, and many local payment methods, \nbut Vipps is likely better for Norwegian familiarity.\n\nReferences:\nVipps MobilePay ePayment docs: https://developer.vippsmobilepay.com/docs/APIs/epayment-api/\nStripe Checkout docs: https://docs.stripe.com/payments/checkout",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "5. Add Vipps later, not now\nFor Norway-first direct payment, Vipps MobilePay ePayment is the natural future option.\n\nWhy:\nVipps is familiar to Norwegian buyers.\nVipps MobilePay’s current ePayment API supports online payments and multiple payment methods.\nTheir docs say ePayment replaces the older eCom API, so avoid building against legacy eCom.\n\nUse Vipps when:\nYou want “Buy now” for available paintings.\nPrices and shipping are predictable.\nYou are ready to handle payment webhooks and order state.\n\nDo not use Vipps yet because:\nDirect payment requires backend logic.\nYou need merchant setup, API keys, test/prod environments, payment status handling, and failure handling.\nYou need to prevent two people from buying the same painting.\nStripe Checkout is a good future alternative if international buyers matter. Stripe gives hosted checkout, card payments, and many local payment methods, \nbut Vipps is likely better for Norwegian familiarity.\n\nReferences:\nVipps MobilePay ePayment docs: https://developer.vippsmobilepay.com/docs/APIs/epayment-api/\nStripe Checkout docs: https://docs.stripe.com/payments/checkout",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
    {
      "id": "MUKrWNjMN9ihaueCHPRFI",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -667.2282869285721,
      "y": 9069.004031550434,
      "width": 2281.860595703125,
      "height": 2624.4,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#2f9e44",
      "backgroundColor": "#e9ecef",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b16",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1103963673,
      "version": 6,
      "versionNonce": 615151161,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1781295692051,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "6. Add a database only when direct commerce/admin exists\nFuture database tables/entities:\nPainting\nCustomer\nInquiry\nOrder\nPayment\nDo not add all of these now.\nFuture schema concept:\nPainting\n- id\n- slug\n- title\n- description\n- medium\n- dimensions\n- priceNok\n- status: draft / available / reserved / sold\n- images\n- createdAt\n- updatedAt\n\nInquiry\n- id\n- paintingId\n- name\n- email\n- phone\n- message\n- status: new / replied / closed\n- createdAt\n\nOrder\n- id\n- paintingId\n- customerId\n- status: pending / paid / cancelled / refunded\n- totalNok\n- createdAt\n\nPayment\n- id\n- orderId\n- provider: vipps / stripe\n- providerReference\n- status\n- createdAt\n\nWhy this order:\nPainting is needed first.\nInquiry becomes useful once you want a record of buyer requests.\nOrder and Payment only matter once online checkout exists.\nCustomer only matters when you need purchase history or account-like behavior.\nBeginner mistake to avoid: creating a full database model before the business process is clear. Good architecture grows from real workflows.",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 6,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "6. Add a database only when direct commerce/admin exists\nFuture database tables/entities:\nPainting\nCustomer\nInquiry\nOrder\nPayment\nDo not add all of these now.\nFuture schema concept:\nPainting\n- id\n- slug\n- title\n- description\n- medium\n- dimensions\n- priceNok\n- status: draft / available / reserved / sold\n- images\n- createdAt\n- updatedAt\n\nInquiry\n- id\n- paintingId\n- name\n- email\n- phone\n- message\n- status: new / replied / closed\n- createdAt\n\nOrder\n- id\n- paintingId\n- customerId\n- status: pending / paid / cancelled / refunded\n- totalNok\n- createdAt\n\nPayment\n- id\n- orderId\n- provider: vipps / stripe\n- providerReference\n- status\n- createdAt\n\nWhy this order:\nPainting is needed first.\nInquiry becomes useful once you want a record of buyer requests.\nOrder and Payment only matter once online checkout exists.\nCustomer only matters when you need purchase history or account-like behavior.\nBeginner mistake to avoid: creating a full database model before the business process is clear. Good architecture grows from real workflows.",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.35
    },
